  "prompt": "What percentage of freshers are accepted into the IIM's every year?",
  "response": "It's difficult to give a precise percentage for the acceptance rate of freshers specifically into IIMs every year because IIMs don't publicly release data specifically segmented by work experience. However, we can make some educated estimations:\n\n*   **Overall Acceptance Rate:** The acceptance rate for the IIMs, even collectively, is very low. It's estimated to be well under 1% (closer to 0.2-0.5%) of all applicants, considering the hundreds of thousands of people who take the CAT exam each year and the relatively limited number of seats across all IIMs.\n\n*   **Proportion of Freshers:** While most IIMs prefer candidates with work experience, they certainly accept freshers. However, freshers generally make up a minority of the incoming class at most of the top IIMs (Ahmedabad, Bangalore, Calcutta, Lucknow). Newer IIMs might have a higher percentage of freshers. The percentage can vary significantly from year to year, and also depends on the specific IIM. Some IIMs (like IIM Kozhikode) are known to encourage a more diverse profile, which includes a healthy mix of freshers.\n\n**Factors to Consider:**\n\n*   **CAT Score:** A high CAT score is absolutely crucial, regardless of work experience. Freshers generally need a higher CAT score than candidates with work experience to compensate for the lack of professional experience.\n*   **Academic Background:** Strong academic performance throughout their school and graduation is vital.\n*   **Diversity:** IIMs are increasingly focusing on diversity (academic background, gender, etc.). If a fresher comes from a non-engineering background, it can be an advantage.\n*   **Performance in WAT/PI:** Freshers must perform exceptionally well in the Written Ability Test (WAT) and Personal Interview (PI) rounds to demonstrate their communication skills, analytical abilities, and overall fit for the program.\n*   **Extracurriculars and Internships:** Having significant achievements in extracurricular activities, certifications, or valuable internships can definitely boost a fresher's application.\n\n**In conclusion:**\n\nWhile it is impossible to give an exact percentage for the acceptance rate of freshers, a *very rough* estimate is that freshers constitute roughly 10-30% of each IIM class. Therefore, to calculate an acceptance rate specific to freshers, the calculation becomes significantly more complex and requires many unsupported assumptions.\n\n**Key takeaway:**\n\nDon't focus too much on the overall acceptance rate. Instead, focus on building a strong profile: aim for a high CAT score, maintain a strong academic record, develop your communication and leadership skills, participate in extracurricular activities, and gain relevant internship experience. This will significantly improve your chances of getting into your desired IIM.\n",
